Split the dataset into training and testing with ratio 8:2

set.seed(123)
ind <- sample(2, nrow(bank_data2), replace = TRUE, prob = c(0.8,0.2))
df_train <- bank_data2[ind == 1,]
df_test <- bank_data2[ind == 2,]
#Undersampling to obtain a more balanced dataset
df_train <- SMOTE(y~., data = df_train, perc.over=100)

Now we create a decision tree model: CART

# install.packages('rpart')
library(rpart)
D_model <- rpart(y ~., data = df_train)
plot(D_model, margin = 0.01)
text(D_model, all = TRUE, use.n = TRUE)

require(rpart.plot) 
## Loading required package: rpart.plot
prp(D_model,        
    faclen=0,           
    fallen.leaves=TRUE, 
    shadow.col="gray",  
    extra=2)

Evaluate model performance

To apply our decision tree to the test dataset, we use the predict() function, as shown in the following line of code:

### Evaluate model performance
pred <- predict(D_model, df_test, type = 'class')
